{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611003"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16188"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16188"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.66,0.03,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8879"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16188"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60101"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10592"},{"type":"tags","id":"10602"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProlactin secretion from the anterior pituitary is under tonic inhibitory control. During breastfeeding, suckling at the nipple triggers neural signals that travel via the spinal cord to modify this inhibitory control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following neurotransmitters provides tonic inhibition of prolactin secretion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acetylcholine","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone","Dopamine","Serotonin","Oxytocin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the key inhibitory factor that normally suppresses prolactin secretion from lactotrophs in the anterior pituitary. During lactation, suckling reduces dopamine release from the hypothalamus, which allows increased prolactin secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetylcholine\u003C/strong\u003E is a neurotransmitter involved in the milk ejection reflex but does not regulate prolactin secretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E controls follicle-stimulating hormone and luteinising hormone release but not prolactin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin\u003C/strong\u003E influences mood and behaviour but does not directly regulate prolactin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin\u003C/strong\u003E stimulates myoepithelial cells for milk ejection but does not control prolactin secretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis system represents an example of negative feedback control, where dopamine provides tonic inhibition that can be removed to allow prolactin secretion when needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dopamine from the hypothalamus normally inhibits prolactin release from lactotrophs in the anterior pituitary.","During lactation, suckling inhibits dopamine release, which removes inhibition of prolactin secretion.","This neuroendocrine reflex pathway involves signals from the nipple through the spinal cord to the hypothalamus."],"references":["Deif R, Burch EM, Azar J, Yonis N, Abou Gabal M, El Kramani N, DakhlAllah D. Dysphoric Milk Ejection Reflex: The Psychoneurobiology of the Breastfeeding Experience. Front Glob Womens Health. 2021 Oct 29;2:669826. doi: 10.3389/fgwh.2021.669826. PMID: 34816221; PMCID: PMC8594038.","Fourman LT, Fazeli PK. Neuroendocrine causes of amenorrhea--an update. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2015 Mar;100(3):812-24. doi: 10.1210/jc.2014-3344. Epub 2015 Jan 12. PMID: 25581597; PMCID: PMC4333037.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60101"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16188"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60101"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T19:47:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T19:48:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8879"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"